01:46.629 --> 01:50.464
[WOMAN SOBBING]

01:50.466 --> 01:53.337
[GUNSHOT]
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

01:56.739 --> 01:58.643
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

01:59.709 --> 02:01.008
[MAN LAUGHS]

02:01.010 --> 02:03.947
[BELL RINGING]

02:08.884 --> 02:11.588
[BELL RINGING]

02:14.591 --> 02:15.857
[MAN GRUNTING]

02:15.859 --> 02:17.792
Shh, shh, shh, shh.

02:17.794 --> 02:21.395
[GRUNTING]

02:21.397 --> 02:24.766
[BELL RINGING]

02:24.768 --> 02:25.800
[LAUGHS]

02:25.802 --> 02:28.272
[BELL RINGING]

02:33.610 --> 02:34.746
Surprised?

02:36.045 --> 02:37.512
It actually starts
to grow on you.

02:37.514 --> 02:38.516
Trust me.

02:45.389 --> 02:46.724
[GUNSHOT]

02:51.694 --> 02:57.499
I would do anything to
erase the memory of that day.

02:57.501 --> 03:00.869
Now, some of us are able
to suppress harsh memories,

03:00.871 --> 03:03.505
but memories are only
part of the truth.

03:03.507 --> 03:05.075
They're not the whole truth.

03:06.810 --> 03:08.312
Let me ask you a question.

03:09.947 --> 03:12.614
What was the last
great meal you had?

03:12.616 --> 03:14.548
Where did you have it?

03:14.550 --> 03:16.518
Who did you have it with?

03:16.520 --> 03:19.054
Well, depending on how
long ago you had this meal,

03:19.056 --> 03:21.790
you may not remember
all the details.

03:21.792 --> 03:23.892
But do you remember
the meal you had the next day

03:23.894 --> 03:25.827
or the day after that?

03:25.829 --> 03:27.498
Vaguely, perhaps, or not at all.

03:28.799 --> 03:30.931
The last time I stood
in front of this committee,

03:30.933 --> 03:33.567
I told you we were very
close to creating a nanobot

03:33.569 --> 03:35.137
that would enhance
the capabilities

03:35.139 --> 03:37.575
of the brain's
recall procedures.

03:39.175 --> 03:40.875
Ladies and gentlemen,

03:40.877 --> 03:44.979
I give you the advanced
memory enhancement nanobot.

03:44.981 --> 03:47.916
Designed to apply itself
to the cells of the hippocampus,

03:47.918 --> 03:49.451
it acts like a light switch,

03:49.453 --> 03:51.018
turning on and off memories
as needed

03:51.020 --> 03:54.989
by regulating a gene
known as TAT-1.

03:54.991 --> 03:58.994
Now, by programming sensory
detail into the nanobots,

03:58.996 --> 04:01.963
we can trace, pinpoint,
and actually recreate

04:01.965 --> 04:07.668
specific memories
based on data provided.

04:07.670 --> 04:11.006
The possibilities of my
technology are endless.

04:11.008 --> 04:14.743
Alzheimer's, amnesia, PTSD.

04:14.745 --> 04:17.913
Any brain-related issue
with memory.

04:17.915 --> 04:20.781
Turning the right memories on...

04:20.783 --> 04:22.052
and the wrong ones off.

04:29.860 --> 04:31.162
Ladies and gentlemen...

04:32.528 --> 04:34.863
this technology
absolutely works,

04:34.865 --> 04:38.936
but it is impossible for me
to demonstrate it...

04:40.603 --> 04:41.838
using mice.

04:44.608 --> 04:47.711
I need a single human subject.

04:50.514 --> 04:51.915
[ELECTRONIC WHIRR]

04:53.016 --> 04:54.185
Thank you.

05:01.257 --> 05:03.058
WOMAN: [CLEARS THROAT]
Thank you for your

05:03.060 --> 05:05.594
entertaining presentation,
Dr. Anderson.

05:05.596 --> 05:08.062
This panel was set up
by the government

05:08.064 --> 05:12.000
to evaluate projects relevant
to current circumstances.

05:12.002 --> 05:15.070
And although your project
is quite remarkable,

05:15.072 --> 05:18.608
we have more critical issues
that plague our streets.

05:20.177 --> 05:23.277
We shall convey our decision
to your research facility.

05:23.279 --> 05:25.081
Thank you for your time.

05:26.916 --> 05:29.853
[SOFT PIANO MUSIC]

05:44.134 --> 05:45.536
WOMAN:
Dr. Anderson?

05:47.069 --> 05:48.473
Dr. Anderson?

05:49.839 --> 05:50.906
That would be me.

05:50.908 --> 05:53.007
Hi, I'm Dr. Rachel Porter.

05:53.009 --> 05:55.043
Mansingh Research Center.

05:55.045 --> 05:57.678
Very impressive
what you said inside.

05:57.680 --> 05:59.014
I thought so.

05:59.016 --> 06:01.615
I'm not sure the panel
felt the same way.

06:01.617 --> 06:03.218
Well, we at the
research center

06:03.220 --> 06:06.253
are very interested in
what you have to offer.

06:06.255 --> 06:07.755
Really, and what's that?

06:07.757 --> 06:09.623
Your nanobots.

06:09.625 --> 06:12.260
We believe that working together
would be mutually beneficial.

06:12.262 --> 06:13.995
You think that?

06:13.997 --> 06:15.997
Right now we're in the process
of a human trial phase

06:15.999 --> 06:17.598
of a government-sanctioned
project,

06:17.600 --> 06:19.601
which, it's not exactly
what you had in mind,

06:19.603 --> 06:21.803
but you'd be able
to see your boys in action.

06:21.805 --> 06:24.242
What do you think?
[HORN HONKS]

06:25.975 --> 06:27.175
You need an answer right now?

06:27.177 --> 06:28.278
The sooner the better.

06:29.812 --> 06:31.779
Be a great opportunity
for you to take your experiment

06:31.781 --> 06:32.880
to the next level, Dr. Anderson.

06:32.882 --> 06:33.949
[HORN HONKS]

06:33.951 --> 06:36.554
[SIREN WAILING]

06:38.288 --> 06:41.889
MAN: <i>We're in a society now
where we expect mass shootings.</i>

06:41.891 --> 06:44.125
And it's possible,
now more than ever,

06:44.127 --> 06:46.827
<i>for an individual to commit.</i>

06:46.829 --> 06:49.163
<i>We're beyond the stage
where we can simply say,</i>

06:49.165 --> 06:51.298
<i>"No, you shouldn't do that."</i>

06:51.300 --> 06:53.168
<i>And I'm aware
that you've been working</i>

06:53.170 --> 06:55.070
<i>with a number of research labs.</i>

06:55.072 --> 06:57.839
<i>Have they been able to achieve
the results that you want?</i>

06:57.841 --> 06:59.707
<i>We're getting closer.</i>

06:59.709 --> 07:02.077
<i>Conventional ethical boundaries
are slowing the work.</i>

07:02.079 --> 07:03.644
<i>In what way?</i>

07:03.646 --> 07:04.980
MAN:
<i>Well, there are restrictions...</i>

07:04.982 --> 07:07.882
Hey, are you sure
you wanna go back there?

07:07.884 --> 07:10.618
...and they've been
there for a long time.

07:10.620 --> 07:12.086
WOMAN:
<i>But if you remove them,</i>

07:12.088 --> 07:13.887
<i>won't you be stepping
on free will?</i>

07:13.889 --> 07:15.757
MAN: <i>But free will doesn't mean
you have the right</i>

07:15.759 --> 07:17.993
<i>to run rampant on an unchecked
impulse and kill people.</i>

07:17.995 --> 07:20.228
<i>We're trying to create a
society where can guarantee</i>

07:20.230 --> 07:22.998
<i>that people
will behave responsibly.</i>

07:23.000 --> 07:25.733
And they can exercise
their own free will

07:25.735 --> 07:27.067
without stepping
on someone else's.

07:27.069 --> 07:30.141
[MACHINE BEEPING]

07:31.307 --> 07:33.978
[SUBDUED MUSIC]

07:53.163 --> 07:54.361
What do you think?

07:54.363 --> 07:55.829
80 percent human?

07:55.831 --> 07:57.201
90 percent human?

07:58.668 --> 08:01.069
Dr. Anderson, Walter Mansingh.

08:01.071 --> 08:02.836
Pleasure.
Nice to meet you.

08:02.838 --> 08:04.375
So glad you could join us.

08:06.810 --> 08:08.743
I see you two have met.

08:08.745 --> 08:11.312
If you'd excuse us, Walter,
I need to brief Dr. Anderson.

08:11.314 --> 08:13.848
Rachel, 95 percent human.

08:13.850 --> 08:14.916
We think.

08:14.918 --> 08:16.086
Enjoy your tour.

08:19.088 --> 08:20.755
Who is this man?

08:20.757 --> 08:22.723
This is Simon Frost.

08:22.725 --> 08:25.694
Convicted criminal
on charges of assault, rape,

08:25.696 --> 08:26.894
and we suspect much worse,

08:26.896 --> 08:28.062
although thanks
to your research,

08:28.064 --> 08:29.930
we'll no longer have to imagine.

08:29.932 --> 08:31.466
Oh, I'm not sure.

08:31.468 --> 08:33.299
Oh, we're following
all the appropriate channels.

08:33.302 --> 08:36.304
He's been put in our care
for a very unique human trial,

08:36.306 --> 08:40.073
which, if successful, will
lead to his eventual release.

08:40.076 --> 08:42.212
If successful,
will actually change the world.

08:50.821 --> 08:52.353
When a person commits
an act that falls

08:52.355 --> 08:54.354
beyond the bounds
of established social morals,

08:54.356 --> 08:56.724
parts of the brain
become hyperactive.

08:56.726 --> 08:58.459
Conversely, parts of the brain
that control

08:58.461 --> 09:01.429
impulsive actions
become more dormant.

09:01.431 --> 09:04.031
Over time,
these behaviors become habits.

09:04.033 --> 09:05.934
Habits become addictions.

09:05.936 --> 09:08.936
All in pursuit of recreating
that first experience.

09:08.938 --> 09:11.071
Pushing the boundaries of risk
on a consistent basis.

09:11.073 --> 09:12.741
Mm-hm.

09:12.743 --> 09:14.908
Drugs and alcohol, these
problems are, for the most part,

09:14.910 --> 09:18.079
manageable, but violence,
consistent abnormal behavior

09:18.081 --> 09:19.480
of such nature
is usually the result

09:19.482 --> 09:20.949
of years of conditioning.

09:20.951 --> 09:22.316
Right.

09:22.318 --> 09:23.383
And all this, I suppose,
is the proposed method

09:23.385 --> 09:24.919
of breaking said condition.

09:24.921 --> 09:25.987
Exactly, but first
we need to establish

09:25.989 --> 09:27.354
a pattern in Simon's behavior.

09:27.356 --> 09:29.223
I assume that's
where I come in.

09:29.225 --> 09:30.791
Excuse me.

09:30.793 --> 09:33.127
I'm wondering, where are
the rest of your people?

09:33.129 --> 09:34.395
A project of this
nature requires

09:34.397 --> 09:36.233
a certain degree of secrecy.

09:38.033 --> 09:40.468
Walter Mansingh cleared
this particular building for us.

09:40.470 --> 09:42.837
And who's filling
Walter Mansingh's pockets?

09:42.839 --> 09:45.272
And that concludes our tour.

09:45.274 --> 09:47.275
Thank you for coming,
Dr. Anderson.

09:47.277 --> 09:49.844
- Pleasure.
- Hope to see you again.

09:49.846 --> 09:51.481
I'm sure you can
find your way out.

09:55.485 --> 09:59.190
[SOFT PIANO MUSIC]

10:03.527 --> 10:06.026
[WAVES CRASHING]

10:06.028 --> 10:07.764
When did she get that tall?

10:13.235 --> 10:14.370
I'm so close, Marie.

10:15.871 --> 10:19.040
I get one subject and this
whole thing is gonna fly.

10:19.042 --> 10:22.310
And we are gonna have
all the time in the world.

10:22.312 --> 10:23.913
We'll see.

10:26.917 --> 10:28.952
Just say the word
and I walk away from it all.

10:30.519 --> 10:31.956
And do what?

10:34.356 --> 10:35.959
I don't know, something.

10:39.528 --> 10:41.462
Anything that doesn't
require me to apply

10:41.464 --> 10:44.398
my awesome,
awesome brain power.

10:44.400 --> 10:46.501
[CHUCKLES]

10:46.503 --> 10:50.405
I really can't see you
doing anything too laborious.

10:50.407 --> 10:52.272
What?

10:52.274 --> 10:53.541
Oh, listen, sister.

10:53.543 --> 10:56.444
These hands only
appear to be soft.

10:56.446 --> 10:59.950
They are capable of some
really light manual labor.

11:02.318 --> 11:06.320
Well, in any case,
I can't let you quit now.

11:06.322 --> 11:07.024
You're too close.

11:08.258 --> 11:11.392
And I am looking forward
to reaping the benefits

11:11.394 --> 11:13.060
of my investment.

11:13.062 --> 11:14.494
Oh.

11:14.496 --> 11:16.430
So that's all I am to you now,
an investment.

11:16.432 --> 11:17.467
Mm-hm.

11:19.201 --> 11:20.602
Okay.

11:20.604 --> 11:21.437
I'm fine with that.

11:22.538 --> 11:25.906
Super-hot, aging,
Jet Li investment.

11:25.908 --> 11:27.041
[MARIE LAUGHS]

11:27.043 --> 11:29.813
[SIREN WAILING]

11:32.115 --> 11:33.314
Do you need help setting up?

11:33.316 --> 11:34.581
Did you get what I asked for?

11:34.583 --> 11:36.316
Yes, of course.

11:36.318 --> 11:37.951
- From his cell phone.
- What's it for?

11:37.953 --> 11:38.987
Sensory detail.

11:38.989 --> 11:40.320
On this instance, it's an image,

11:40.322 --> 11:41.488
but it could be a
sound or a smell.

11:41.490 --> 11:43.226
It's what cues memory recall.

11:45.495 --> 11:46.927
Perfect.
So, what I'm doing now

11:46.929 --> 11:48.563
is giving the information

11:48.565 --> 11:51.232
to the nanobots so they'll
know exactly the memory

11:51.234 --> 11:52.532
that you're trying to pinpoint.

11:52.534 --> 11:54.535
And...

11:54.537 --> 11:56.373
- done.
- Already?

11:57.474 --> 11:59.143
Well, that's the easy part.

12:00.976 --> 12:02.377
Portable FMRI.

12:02.379 --> 12:03.478
Atomic magnetometry.

12:03.480 --> 12:04.914
Ah, very good.

12:06.383 --> 12:08.583
Okay, I could use that hand now.

12:08.585 --> 12:10.086
Right here, please.

12:11.187 --> 12:13.990
[MACHINE BEEPING]

12:27.604 --> 12:28.906
Here you go.

12:34.311 --> 12:35.512
Is this safe?

12:37.580 --> 12:39.450
Let's find out, shall we?

12:42.052 --> 12:43.954
We should probably
be seated for this.

12:47.256 --> 12:49.022
It's gonna take a few minutes
for the nanobots

12:49.024 --> 12:50.590
to reach the hippocampus.

12:50.592 --> 12:52.395
That way they can formulate
the memory for Simon.

12:56.666 --> 12:59.066
Please remember
this is a prototype.

12:59.068 --> 13:00.471
Results may vary.

13:03.005 --> 13:05.339
[EXHALES]

13:05.341 --> 13:08.544
[ELECTRONIC WHIRR]

13:14.517 --> 13:18.055
[BASS-HEAVY ELECTRONIC MUSIC]

13:24.293 --> 13:26.393
Are we in his memory?

13:26.395 --> 13:27.661
No, not exactly.

13:27.663 --> 13:29.664
More like a shared
reconsolidation.

13:29.666 --> 13:31.465
His memories are
re-encoded and transmitted

13:31.467 --> 13:33.133
into new memories for us,

13:33.135 --> 13:34.736
which our brain interprets
in the third person.

13:34.738 --> 13:37.704
Think of it like
watching a movie clip.

13:37.706 --> 13:39.373
It's the only way our brains
can rationally make sense

13:39.375 --> 13:42.312
of something that wasn't
ours to begin with.

13:55.524 --> 13:57.060
[LAUGHING]

14:13.342 --> 14:15.475
We need strawberries.

14:15.477 --> 14:18.112
Do you wanna play a
game of darts, babe?

14:18.114 --> 14:20.084
You have a games room in here?

14:28.224 --> 14:30.527
This is my games room, babe.

14:36.432 --> 14:39.834
Darts, my favorite.

14:39.836 --> 14:42.369
[LAUGHS]

14:42.371 --> 14:45.373
Now, what you're experiencing
is voluntary muscle paralysis

14:45.375 --> 14:48.175
due to blocked
impulse transmission.

14:48.177 --> 14:49.810
Dizzy, unable to move.

14:49.812 --> 14:51.079
[WOMAN MOANS]

14:51.081 --> 14:52.579
Choking.

14:52.581 --> 14:56.283
Head still fully processing
everything we're doing.

14:56.285 --> 14:58.618
[WOMAN GASPING]

14:58.620 --> 15:02.158
Best part is that you
can still feel pain.

15:06.729 --> 15:09.763
[FLESH TEARING]

15:09.765 --> 15:11.199
[GAGS]

15:11.201 --> 15:12.269
Enough.

15:14.269 --> 15:17.240
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

15:19.708 --> 15:21.711
Your research
up until this point...

15:23.212 --> 15:27.214
what your nanobots
are capable of, it's astounding.

15:27.216 --> 15:29.119
You're right.
This isn't what I had in mind.

15:32.322 --> 15:34.589
His... his crimes are real.

15:34.591 --> 15:36.791
This is happening.

15:36.793 --> 15:40.127
Dr. Anderson, this is the world
that we live in.

15:40.129 --> 15:42.131
We have to do something
to fix it.

15:46.870 --> 15:48.337
Let me show you something.

15:49.772 --> 15:51.272
Please.

15:51.274 --> 15:53.141
This is my labor of love.

15:53.143 --> 15:55.343
A modified enzyme
that gels with enzymes

15:55.345 --> 15:57.377
sending messages to the brain.

15:57.379 --> 16:00.348
When it detects hyperactivity
in the wrong parts of the brain,

16:00.350 --> 16:03.718
it fires symptoms of a common,
yet painful, human ailment.

16:03.720 --> 16:06.286
This one I prepared for Simon,
for example,

16:06.288 --> 16:07.691
triggers migraines.

16:09.424 --> 16:10.824
So when the wood
in his pants grows,

16:10.826 --> 16:13.493
he's subjected
to severe headaches.

16:13.495 --> 16:15.231
That's one way to put it.

16:16.666 --> 16:18.565
Over time, his brain will learn

16:18.567 --> 16:21.935
that what once was
pleasurable is now painful.

16:21.937 --> 16:23.603
Right.

16:23.605 --> 16:25.205
So, if we can test this

16:25.207 --> 16:26.840
in Simon's recreated memory
successfully,

16:26.842 --> 16:28.542
you'll know if your treatment
is the real deal.

16:28.544 --> 16:29.312
Precisely.

16:30.712 --> 16:33.848
Why should I help someone
who wasn't human to begin with?

16:33.850 --> 16:36.383
I think you've misunderstood
our intentions, Dr. Anderson.

16:36.385 --> 16:37.852
It's not just him we're helping.

16:37.854 --> 16:41.589
It's the countless victims
of future violence.

16:41.591 --> 16:42.592
Think about it.

16:43.693 --> 16:50.330
If this works, funding,
human subjects, you name it.

16:50.332 --> 16:52.333
Come on, let me show you.

16:52.335 --> 16:55.538
[ELECTRONIC WHIRR]

16:59.676 --> 17:02.278
[UPTEMPO ELECTRONIC MUSIC]

17:08.750 --> 17:09.983
RACHEL:
Strange.

17:09.986 --> 17:11.551
What?

17:11.554 --> 17:13.753
She's wearing a sweater.

17:13.756 --> 17:16.423
I knew our memories
were subject to change

17:16.425 --> 17:17.724
every time we recall them,

17:17.727 --> 17:21.528
but seeing it happen
is frightening.

17:21.530 --> 17:24.931
Yeah, makes you question
your belief in them, doesn't it?

17:24.933 --> 17:26.569
We need strawberries.

17:28.637 --> 17:30.307
Do you wanna play a
game of darts, babe?

17:32.976 --> 17:35.245
You have a games
room in here, too?

17:39.882 --> 17:41.585
The moment of truth.

17:44.287 --> 17:46.923
[COUGHING]

17:50.660 --> 17:52.229
What's going on?

17:54.497 --> 17:56.533
[YELLS]

18:01.003 --> 18:03.638
What's going on?
Oh, my God, are you...

18:03.640 --> 18:05.342
Babe, what's going on?

18:08.344 --> 18:09.913
[SIMON GROANS]

18:17.353 --> 18:20.353
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

18:20.355 --> 18:22.960
[MACHINE BEEPING]

18:33.736 --> 18:35.036
Senator.

18:35.038 --> 18:36.569
Senator Edward Frost,

18:36.571 --> 18:39.539
may I please present
Dr. Adam Anderson.

18:39.541 --> 18:40.908
So pleased to meet you.

18:40.910 --> 18:42.809
- Hi.
- I've heard lots about you.

18:42.811 --> 18:44.778
And I'm told that we were
correct in assuming

18:44.780 --> 18:47.715
you are the missing piece
to our puzzle.

18:47.717 --> 18:48.785
Please.

18:50.686 --> 18:55.355
Yes, well, I'd say there's
still a few pieces missing yet.

18:55.357 --> 18:56.923
I think what Dr. Anderson means
is that...

18:56.925 --> 18:59.059
Walter. Walter, please.

18:59.061 --> 19:01.027
Let's let the doctors tell us.

19:01.029 --> 19:02.930
There's been
tremendous progress.

19:02.932 --> 19:04.465
Thanks to Dr. Anderson,

19:04.467 --> 19:06.100
